Pin‘ freshman wins Pa. State Fair Queen competition

 

By Tracey Katz
For The Pitt News

Feather Thomas, an _l8-year-
old Pitt nursing student, won
the 1996 Pennsylvania State
Fair Queen title on Jan. 20 at
the Hershey Lodge and
Convention Center in
Harrisburg.

It was no surprise Feather
was selected from 44 girls to
be awarded the honor because
she is no stranger to the spot-
light.

In 1995, Feather took second
runner up in Butler’s Junior

"Miss contest and also received

the Presence and Composure
Award. The following year, she

won the World Beginning-

Two-Baton Championship.
While attending Knoch High
School in Butler County,
Feather was an honor student
and also a recipient of the
Knights of Knowledge Award.
She was a majorette in the
marching band, a feature
twirler her senior year and also
a student baton instructor.
Thomas was also a member of
the Ski, Spanish, Pep and
Senior Cabinet clubs, and a
student council representative.
Feather’s decision to enter
Butler’s Fair Queen contest
was a spur of the moment deci-
sion. “My grandmother found
out about the competition
when I was on vacation with
my family. I never thought I
would win, it was just some-

thing Ivdid for fun,” said‘

Thomas.

Before reaching the state
level, Feather was chosen from
11 girls to represent her county.
She then packed her bags and
was off to the state,competi-
tion. ' -
The contest lasted for two
days. Forty-four girls compet-
ed for the title and were judged
on their poise and appearance,
speeches and their essays and
interviews.

Thomas said getting pre-
pared for the competition was
an event in itself. It was a chal-
lenge both physically and men-
tally. Her first step was to lose
weight. “I had about three or

four months to lose the ‘fresh- «

man 15’ so I could fit into my
prom dress. It was so hard. I
never worried about what I ate
in high school, because I.was
always active.”

Also, Thomas says she is not
one to get all dolled up. “It
took a long time to get my hair
and make-up on. The stuff they
put on me was stage make-up
so we could be seen out in the
audience. All I wanted to do
was wash my face.”

Mentally, Feather told her-

self that this was just a compe--

tition. “I did it for fun and to
meet other people, and if I won
that would be a bonus. If I
didn’t win, I had a lot of fun
trying.”

Feather said the worst thing
about the competition was the
constant waiting for the next
event to happen. “When I was

waiting to have my interview ‘

with the judges, my hands

started to tingle. I was so ner-
vous.”

The judges cut from 44 to
five girls based upon speeches,
appearance and interviews.
“The judges look and speak to
so many girls that you have to
do something that sticks in
their minds,” said Thomas.

After the cuts, the five girls
who had advanced were taken
off stage and individually
brought back on to answer this
question: If you were named
Pennsylvania State Fair Queen,
what would you do to promote
the values of the fairs?

When choosing a winner,

judges looked for the girl who
got right to the heart of the
question and gave a clear
answer. That’s what Thomas
did. “When they announced
me as the winner, I covered my
face in shock,” she said. ‘
Thomas felt she won the
contest because in her answer
she gave the judges something
to remember, as opposed to
winning solely on her beauty.
Thomas didn’t feel that this
was like a beauty contest. She
saw it as a great confidence
builder, not degrading. “This
really brought out the best in
me. I did it because it was

great way to earn money for
school.”

Thomas said she won
because she showed the judges
she could keep cool under
pressure. “It wasn’t based on
just looks. I gave an honest
answer, and I didn’t ramble on
and on.” ‘

As the Pennsylvania State
Fair Queen, Feather received a
$1,000 ‘college scholarship.
She is expected to promote
fairs throughout the state this
year, and she will appear in
various parades. .

On Feb. 5, Feather began her
duties by meeting with the

state legislature. She will also

have the opportunity to be pre— 9

sented, on the floor, at a state
legislature meeting and give a
speech.

Even though Feather carries
these new responsibilities,
school is still her top priority.

“I’m not sure what type of I

nurse I want to be yet. I’ll have
to wait until I start clinical to
figure that out.”

As for more beauty pageants,
she says she might like to do it
again. “I don’t know if it’s
really for me, but if I do it
again I would do it to get
money for college.”

