‘ We’ve all heard the jokes about “Dr. Death” Jack Kevorkian and his
Deathmobile. A quick morbid chuckle, maybe a little smile, and the dead-
ly impact of the jokes is overlooked Unfortunately for many people, there

' is nothing at all funny about the debate over the right to die.

Far too many people lie in hospital beds around the country, waiting
until it ﬁnally just ends. Many of them aren’t even aware that they are
alive, since the only thing keeping them that way is a set of machines
which keeps their organs functioning. They have extensive brain damage,
and will never recover to a normally functioning state, but they are kept
alive through the miracles of modern science and the modem legal system.

Thanks to medical science, it is practically possible to sustain life indeﬁ-
nitely, though the person may be brain—dead And thanks to the legal sys-

S tem, it is practically possible to keep a person breathing even if they don’t

want it.

The issue in front of the Supreme Cotnt right now goes beyond whether
or not doctors should be able to help terminally ill patients commit suicide.
The Court is now being asked to decide whether or not vital life support
may be removed from a man who is conscious but cannot function at all
without the help of machines. A . V

Michael Martin cannot sit up, cannot eat, cannot even breathe without
help. He suffered extensive brain damage when his car was hit by a train,
and he is almost totally paralyzed. Before the accident, he had told his wife

9 (according to her) that he never wanted to be kept alive by machines. His

wife has sued in several courts to have life support removed, and to let her
husband die. The Michigan Supreme Court said no, since there was no
proof that he would have wanted that ,
  The standard for withdrawing life support is Clear evidence that the
patient wanted that The Supreme Court established this non-policy in
1990, when they allowed that patients have the right to refuse life-saving
treatment. But in the absence of a living will, how can a family provide
clear evidence of a comatose patient’s wishes? You can’t ask the patient,
you can only ask the family. _

The main problem with this non—policy is that the decision is largely left

. up to the judge hearing the case. Though judges are not supposed to let

personal opinion interfere with a ruling, the Supreme Court basically invit-

' ed all judges to do just that. A judge in favor of_a patient’s right to dieeould

take the word of one family member as “clear evidence,” while a judge
opposed to it could deny that an entire family’s testimony was insufﬁcient
proof. -
Now that the Marlins’ case is before the Supreme Court, there should be
a decisive ruling regarding the right to die. Since patients are allowed to
refuse treatment already, they should also have the right to die. Right now,
too much is left to the decision of the state and the courts. The patients and
their advocates are the only ones who should decide whether life support is
withdrawn

