bless.” According to Watson‘, his investment in reli-
gion has paid off exponentially. ’

“My mom has always brought me up learning
about God,” he said. “But I think after I went blind,
my life has completely improved. Some people
might find that hard to understand, but being blind
has caused me to grow up some.”

Watson was forced to grow up quicker than any-
one expected- His eye problems began when he got
severe pinkeye. Then complications set in, so he had
the infection removed. Watson healed quickly, and
scar tissue developed behind his right eye. Because
he had scar tissue, his retina kept detaching. Every
time it was reattached by laser, cells were killed in
the eye. His eye problems then spread to his left eye.
“We really‘don’t know what caused it,” he said. This
went on for about four years, until his vision, once

I20/20, was gone.

-“The first thing I thought of was I wouldn’t be
able to play football,” Watson said. “I didn’t really
think of the other things.”

Watson said it helped that he was a child when he
went blind because he didn’t have any preconcep-
tions about what a blind person should be like.
Although it was a gradual adjustment, Watson said it
was just a matter of time to learn Braille, to figure
out what clothes to wear and simply to get around. ‘

When Watson got older, some people mentioned to
his family that he should try wrestling. So he asked
his high school coach if he could join the Central
High School wrestling team. His coach obliged, and
before he knew it, Watson was making waves in the
Philadelphia public league.

Like anything else, wrestling was a learning
process. Toibegin, it’s a simple touch start, and he
must always maintain contact. Once he mastered
that, it was just a matter of time before Watson
moved up to the varsity. Wrestling against all “see-
ing capable” opponents, Watson was named honor-
able mention in the Philadelphia public league as a
junior. As asenior, he went 9-1, which earned him
third~team all-public league and the Sportsman of
the Year. —

“High school was a lot of fun,” Watson said, smil-
ing. “This is ajob.”

Watson was referring tocollegiate wrestling, more
specifically, the grueling daily practices and the
everyday interactions with his teammates. At first,
Watson said his teammates didn’t know how to treat
him.

“I think sometimes the guys didn’t want to get too
close because they didn’t know what to say or they
didn’t want to offend him,” Stottlemyer said. ,

Now, Watson said that the guys treat him like any-
bodyelse, which is exactly what he wants. Just the

other week at the Bell Atlantic Scholar-Athlete. lun-
cheon, teammate Larry Sprecher told all the guys at
the tableinot to tell Watson where his piece of pie
was because he wanted it for himself. “He was
laughing about it,” Sprecher said. “He has a real
good personality. We kind of joke about him being
blind, but in a good sense. He gets along good with
everybody.”

In warmups before practice, Watson runs with his
right hand on a teammate’s shoulder. Then it gets a
tad bit trickier —— fireman carries. Watson slings his
partner over his shoulder and almost rams him into

the wall. When he puts him down, they laugh and

continue to run.

Watson said he’s not sure if he will try out again -

next year. He said he might get involved in some-
thing else, maybe a fraternity.

“Everybody has a purpose here,”_Watson_ said.
“And I_ think me joining wrestling is part of that pur-
pose because I love to wrestle. It’s not the main
thing, but it’s part of a bigger thing in store in the
future.

“Sometimes I might be a little sad because I can’t
see, that I may be missing out on certain things. But
it doesn’t bother me because spiritually. I-know I
won’t be blind forever. I feel this is for a reason. I
don’t know the full picture of it now, but I will

